    <section id="living-with" class="content-section">
      <h2>Living with hyperthyroidism</h2>
      <p>Hyperthyroidism is one of the most common conditions in older cats, and in many ways one of the more manageable ones — there are effective treatments, and most cats respond well. Three of our cats had it: Artie, who had planned radioactive iodine treatment before his neurological decline made it impossible; Murphy, who had a brief hyperthyroid period before her cancer diagnosis; and Sorbet, who is currently managed for it alongside CKD, FIV, and hypertension.</p>
      <p>The part that catches owners off guard is the CKD connection. Hyperthyroidism artificially increases blood flow to the kidneys, which can make kidney function appear better than it actually is. Treat the thyroid, and kidney markers often rise. This means the treatment decision is more complex than it first appears — and it is a conversation worth having carefully before committing to permanent treatment.</p>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--amber">
        <strong>The thing vets don't always explain:</strong> Before radioactive iodine or surgery, many specialists recommend trialling medication first — to see how kidney values respond when the thyroid is controlled. If kidney function drops significantly on the trial, the treatment plan may need to change. Ask about this specifically.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocacy" class="content-section">
      <h2>What good advocacy looks like</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li><strong>Ask about a medication trial before permanent treatment.</strong> Radioactive iodine is the gold standard for a reason, but trialling methimazole first to observe the kidney response is standard best practice. If it hasn't been mentioned, raise it.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask specifically how kidney values have changed on treatment.</strong> This is the most important variable in the treatment decision. You need the actual numbers, not just "the kidneys look okay."</li>
        <li><strong>Ask what monitoring is required for long-term medication.</strong> If permanent treatment isn't appropriate, ongoing medication has its own requirements — follow-up bloodwork intervals, what to watch for. Get specific on the plan.</li>
        <li><strong>If your cat has multiple conditions, ask how the treatment choice accounts for all of them.</strong> For a cat with hyperthyroidism, CKD, and hypertension, each treatment decision affects the others. Raise the full picture.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

